    <abstract>Lu Dadong and Lis Jung Lu discuss the largest characters carved in Shandong (HDS 8, EG
        1, JS, YC 1) in terms of their calligraphy which is classified as "Flying White Script".
        They stress the three- dimensional qualities of the carving, with over-lapping strokes
        filled in with parallel lines imitating the traces a brush would leave on paper. They call
        this new technique also "character-sculptures" 字雕。 This style has probably to been seen in
        connection with the mixed style of Zhuan and Lishu that was en vogue during the Qi 齐 and
        Liang 梁 dynasties in the south. Nevertheless, the Flying White style giant characters of the
        Buddha names carved in Shandong has to be seen as a means to express the religious
        significance of the work. </abstract>
